rg/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aSociology has long had approaches to describing the ways in which social memory is enacted through ritual, language, art, architecture, and institutions-phenomena whose persistence over time and capacity for a shared storage of the past was set in contrast to fleeting individual memory. But the question of how new media changes that equation is very much up in the air-how, in the age of digital computing, instant updating, and interconnection in real time, is social memory created and enacted? This collection offers a set of essays that discuss the new technology of memory from a variety of perspectives that explicitly investigate their impact on the very concept of the social.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArchives. 0aCollective memory. 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspects. 0aIdentity (Psychology) and mass media. 4aArchiving, Conservation and Digitization. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aArchive theory, social memory studies, digital technologies, media archaeology, media ecology.1 aBerry, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlom, Ina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlom, Ina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErnst, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoffey, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausken, Liv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g